{{Refimprove|date=January 2010}} The '''Toy Symphony''' (full title: ''[[Cassation (music)|Cassation]] in G major for toys, 2 [[oboe]]s, 2 [[Horn (instrument)|horns]], [[string section|strings]] and [[Figured bass|continuo]]'') is a musical work with parts for toy instruments.
It was long reputed to be the work of [[Joseph Haydn]],<ref>p. 201, Ewen (1965) David. Upper Saddle River, New Jersey ''The Complete Book of Classical Music'' Prentice-Hall</ref> but later scholarship suggested that it was actually written by [[Leopold Mozart]].<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web|author=Description by Uncle Dave Lewis |url=http://www.allmusic.com/composition/toy-symphony-cassation-for-toys-2-oboes-2-horns-strings-in-g-major-formerly-k-63-mc0002374551 |title=Toy Symphony (Cassation), for toys, 2 oboes, 2 horns & strings in G major (formerly K. 63) – Leopold Mozart &#124; Details, Parts / Movements and Recordings |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2014-08-05}}</ref> Its authorship is still disputed, however, and other composers have been proposed as the symphony's true author, including Joseph Haydn's younger brother [[Michael Haydn]], who purportedly contributed movements to the work.<ref name=benstock>{{cite book |last=Benstock, |first=Seymour |date=June 14, 2013 |title=Did You Know?: A Music Lover's Guide to Nicknames, Titles, and Whimsy |url= |location=USA |publisher=Trafford Publishing |page=194 |isbn=9781466972926}}</ref>
Recent research on a newly found manuscript suggests the Austrian [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] monk Edmund Angerer (1740–1794) to be the author.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musikland-tirol.at/printable/kindersinfonie.php|title=15. Wer komponierte die weltbekannte Kindersinfonie?|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301062111/http://www.musikland-tirol.at/printable/kindersinfonie.php|archivedate=1 March 2012|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref> If Angerer's manuscript is the original, the Toy Symphony was originally written not in G but rather in C.{{efn|See the title page, including [[incipit]] in staff notation, at {{cite web|url=http://www.musikland-tirol.at/images/notenberchtoldsgadenmusiktable50.jpg|title='Toy Symphony', Title Page}}}} These findings, however, are disputed among scholars. There is reason to believe that the true composer will likely never be known, in whole or in part, given its confused origins and the paucity of related manuscript sources.
