{{Infobox artifact | name = Vače Belt-Plate | image = | image2 = | image_caption = | material = bronze | size = height: {{convert|28.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} | writing = | created = 5th century BC | discovered = [[Hallstatt Archaeological Site in Vače]], at the time [[Austria-Hungary]] (now [[Slovenia]]) | location = [[Naturhistorisches Museum|Natural History Museum in Vienna]] | id = }} The '''Vače Belt-Plate''' ({{lang-sl|pasna spona z Vač}} or {{lang|sl|vaška spona}}, {{lang-de|Gürtelblech von Vače}}) is one of the best examples of [[Illyrian art]] and [[toreutics|toreutic art]].
==Discovery== The Vače Belt-Plate was discovered at the [[Hallstatt Archaeological Site in Vače]], [[Slovenia]], where several Illyrian [[Situla (vessel)|situlae]] were found, the best known of which is the [[Vače Situla]].
==The artifact== The belt-plate dates to the 5th century BC and is displayed at the [[Naturhistorisches Museum|Vienna Natural History Museum]]. It is 28.5&nbsp;cm long and depicts five figures, four of which are warriors in combat. Two of the central warriors are on horseback.<ref>{{harvnb|Stipčević|1989}}.</ref> These may be depictions of mythological events.<ref>{{sl icon}} [http://www.szi-dunaj.at/prireditve/10_01_06_fotos.html Situla Display Announcement], Slovene Research Institute, January 2006, [[Vienna]]</ref>
